<article>
    <h1>Ways to rest and re&#xAD;lax 3 TAKE A WALK IN NA&#xAD;TURE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201223/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-23"><time>2020-12-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE LIV&#xAD;ING WELL</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Escape from the hus­tle and bus­tle of the city and ex­plore some of Sin­ga­pore’s walk­ing or cy­cling trails at parks, gar­dens and park con­nec­tors for fresh air and tran­quil­lity.</p>
    <p>Be­sides be­ing pleas­ing to the eye, green­ery is also ben­e­fi­cial for an in­di­vid­ual’s mental, phys­i­cal and emo­tional well-be­ing.</p>
    <p>There are six ther­a­peu­tic gar­dens in ar­eas such as HortPark, Pung­gol Wa­ter­way Park and Telok Blan­gah Hill Park that are de­signed to calm and lift the moods of vis­i­tors.</p>
    <p>Mr Ng Cheow Kheng, group di­rec­tor of hor­ti­cul­ture and com­mu­nity gar­den­ing at the Na­tional Parks Board, said it has worked with part­ners on many re­search projects to quan­tify the ben­e­fits of green­ery for Sin­ga­pore­ans.</p>
    <p>“One study found that ther­a­peu­tic hor­ti­cul­ture may po­ten­tially boost im­mu­nity and mod­er­ate ge­ri­atric con­di­tions, in­clud­ing in­flam­ma­tory dis­eases, de­men­tia and de­pres­sion,” he said.</p>

